author: @Gigusx
text: I was wondering how the process of writing an entire app with ChatGPT would look like so it's been interesting to watch :) I'm doing a project with the help of it but a bit more complex (it's a full-stack Vue app) and so far I've noticed a few things: - The quality of the prompts really makes a difference, a lot of the time you'll get better answers if you spend some more time on writing the prompt. I feel like I've been learning how to prompt ChatGPT better to get what I want during this experiment, but I haven't tried giving it the entire code (blocks) yet (have always assumed that the context of the conversation and what it has just given me will be enough) so I'll have to try that. - The code you get nearly always needs to be debugged, but it's still a great starting point given you understand what you got. If you don't, I imagine debugging it will be a drag. - Even more amazing for boilerplates (Vue components in my case), saves a ton of time. I haven't tried asking it to write me any tests yet so I'll have to test it out. - I often struggle with ChatGPT's character limit. In longer replies it'll cut off the message and when you ask it to continue, sometimes it'll just continue and sometimes it'll start writing new code, and even weirder - sometimes it'll write a continuation of a code it hasn't written 👀. Regenerating doesn't help a whole lot. - Also, I don't recommend regenerating WHILE it's answering, and I think it's the argument against that ChatGPT has the entire answer readily available the moment it starts replying (I've seen some good arguments in other comments as well), because if you stop generating and immediately regenerate as it's answering, it'll go really dumb and work with different information than before. Though it could be that there's something going funky when you do that and you're not supposed to do that.  All in all, I need to test it a lot more but it's been pretty fun so far. Do you think it has improved for writing code since January, if you still use it, and have you tried ChatGPT 4 yet? I'm pretty excited for the latter because I imagine I'll be able to give it a screenshot of a design and it'll spit out the entire markup, components, and logic based on it. It'll probably still require a lot of editing but damn it'll save so much time :D What they're doing with Copilot is pretty cool too!

author: @pavanpanchangam5785
text: import os import openai import gradio as gr  #if you have OpenAI API key as an environment variable, enable the below #openai.api_key = os.getenv("OPENAI_API_KEY")  #if you have OpenAI API key as a string, enable the below openai.api_key = "xxxxxx"  start_sequence = "\nAI:" restart_sequence = "\nHuman: "  def openai_create(prompt):      response = openai.Completion.create(     model="text-davinci-003",     prompt=prompt,     temperature=0.9,     max_tokens=150,     top_p=1,     frequency_penalty=0,     presence_penalty=0.6,     stop=[" Human:", " AI:"]     )      return response.choices[0].text  def chatgpt_clone(input, conversation_history):     conversation_history = conversation_history or []     s = list(sum(conversation_history, ()))     s.append(input)     inp = ' '.join(s)     output = openai_create(inp)     # Add some humor and friendliness to the response     if "joke" in input.lower():         output = output.replace("Why did", "Haha! Why did")     elif "pun" in input.lower():         output = output.replace("Why", "I'm feeling punny today, so why")     output = output.replace("AI:", "Friendly AI:")     conversation_history.append((input, output))     return conversation_history, conversation_history  def get_sidebar_entries():     conversations = gr.outputs.Textbox(label="Conversations")     new_conversation = gr.inputs.Textbox(label="New Conversation")     regenerate_response = gr.inputs.Checkbox(label="Regenerate Response")     stop_generating = gr.inputs.Checkbox(label="Stop Generating")     return conversations, new_conversation, regenerate_response, stop_generating  def get_output_entries():     conversation_history = gr.outputs.Textbox(label="Conversation History")     response = gr.outputs.Textbox(label="Response")     return conversation_history, response   def chatgpt_wrapper(conversations, new_conversation, regenerate_response, stop_generating):     if new_conversation:         conversations.append([new_conversation, []])     conversation_choices = [c[0] for c in conversations]     if not conversation_choices:         return conversations, "", ""     conversation_choice = gr.Interface.dropdown(conversation_choices, label="Conversation")()     if not conversation_choice:         return conversations, "", ""     conversation_history = conversations[conversation_choice][1]     output_interface = gr.Interface(fn=chatgpt_clone, inputs=[gr.inputs.Textbox(label="Message")], outputs=[gr.outputs.Textbox(label="Response")])     response = ""     while not response and not stop_generating:         output = output_interface("", conversation_history).args[-1]         if regenerate_response:             response = output_interface("", conversation_history).args[-1]         else:             response = output     conversations[conversation_choice][1] = conversation_history     return conversations, conversation_history, response  conversations = []  sidebar_entries = get_sidebar_entries() output_entries = get_output_entries()  sidebar = gr.Interface(     fn=chatgpt_wrapper,     inputs=sidebar_entries,     outputs=output_entries,     title="AI Assistant",     description="The assistant is helpful, creative, clever, and very friendly.",     theme="compact" ) sidebar.launch_in_browser() here is my version of the code

author: @LordoftheLamerS
text: I asked ChatGPT about pre-prompt, he is the answer:  "The pre-prompt for OpenAI's GPT-3 language model, which is what ChatGPT is based on, is not a fixed length. It uses a context-based approach to generate text, meaning that the length of the pre-prompt can vary based on the context of the input.  For example, if the pre-prompt provides more context or information, it may be longer, while a shorter pre-prompt might only include the question being asked. The length of the pre-prompt is determined by the developers and can be adjusted based on the specific use case or application."

author: @AlericResident
text: No, chatgpt doesn't think. Why are you saying? It's just huge text completion neural network. It generates text that look like what you'd expect having seen all texts on the internet without understanding it. If you ask a question then the most likely continuation is an anwser with a solution (given its preprompt) and that "answer" has probably a high correlation with a correct answer if that answer exists on the internet. But chatgpt itself is not sentient, does not think, has no feelings, hardly anything you can call memory (maybe a few kilobytes per chat) and doesn't understand ANYTHING.

author: @andki234
text: As a language model AI, I am designed to generate responses as quickly as possible while also ensuring the quality and accuracy of the information provided. However, there might be some delays that are intentional in order to ensure that the responses generated are of the highest quality and to prevent errors or inaccuracies. Additionally, this delays can be used to prevent overloading the servers and ensure that the service remains available to all users.  Yes, that's correct. Delays can be introduced to prevent overloading the servers and ensure that the service remains available and responsive to all users. It also helps to maintain a balance between the service availability and the response time.  By introducing a small delay in the responses, it can help to prevent the system from being overwhelmed by too many requests at once. This can help to ensure that the service remains available and responsive for all users, and that the responses generated are of the highest quality and accuracy. Additionally, it can help to prevent errors or inaccuracies that could occur if the system was overwhelmed by too many requests at once.  It's important to note that the delay time is not constant and it is adjusted dynamically based on the load of the servers and the system resources.

text: ChatGPT is an InstructGPT model — there is a paper on that. InstructGPT = GPT3 + additional training via Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback. text: import numpy as np from numba import cuda  # Define the number of qubits in the 3D cube array n_qubits = 8  # Create a 3D array of qubits on the GPU qubits_gpu = cuda.to_device(np.random.randint(2, size=(n_qubits, n_qubits, n_qubits)))  # Define a CUDA kernel to apply a quantum gate operation to the qubits @cuda.jit def apply_gate_kernel(qubits_gpu, weights):     # Get the 3D coordinates of the current thread     x, y, z = cuda.grid(3)     # Apply the gate operation to the qubit at the current thread's coordinates     qubits_gpu[x, y, z] = (qubits_gpu[x, y, z] + weights[x, y, z]) % 2  # Apply the quantum gate operation to the qubits weights = cuda.to_device(np.random.rand(n_qubits, n_qubits, n_qubits)) apply_gate_kernel[(n_qubits, n_qubits, n_qubits), 1](qubits_gpu, weights)  # Copy the qubits back to the host qubits = qubits_gpu.copy_to_host()  # Print the state of the qubits print(qubits)

text: First and foremost, congratulations on the babies!!!  I think the last couple of minutes of your video are very valuable and people should make a note, if not already noticed, that ChatGPT can be used to build simple applications, simple websites and that without no big knowledge from the requestor. the best part is, if you run into an error, it will provide you a solution. And this is very very helpful. You learn better like this because you get also explanation.   As example, I am in no way a programmer. Just hobby stuff and nothing big. And yet, thanks to ChatGPT we wrote together one script, then when I decided to create something similar, the errors which I was getting were very similar and i was dealing alone with them, not needed the Bot. Hence, it has quite the positives for your learning curve as well.

author: @Crayphor
text: I've been able to get chatGPT to give a transcript of the conversation up to that point. I could not get it to reveal a pre-prompt though.  Also, I think that chatGPT's reinforcement learning is key to it's performance. The way that they say they did it is through ranking four responses by quality. Then a discriminator learns how to rank the model output with that data and the model uses that discriminator's rankings in its loss function. Instead of tweaking prompts and modifying regexes to find and remove every edge case, this reinforcement learning process can learn to find edge cases unseen by humans.

text: I don't think it's slowed-down, remember, the generations are done autoregressively and the models are already loaded on the GPUs, which means that you can either wait for the complete output (which can take some time even if every token costs like 3ms to generate), or you can print the output one token at a time and spare the humans some impatience.
